@@eThe Arroyo -- Shoreward Assessors' Conversion Study@@N

The @@yShoreward Assessors@@N study the Arroyo as a @@yprecedent case@@N.
That dry canyon solved the same problem we solve daily: how do you
translate one system of obligation into another when both share no
common authority?

The Arroyo converted @@ywater volume into legal obligation@@N. Mafdet's
Shoreward Conversion translates @@yinland charter law into maritime
risk law@@N. The mechanism differs. The @@gprinciple is identical@@N: a
threshold where one jurisdiction's terms must be expressed in
another's language, witnessed and attested before cargo moves.

The Arroyo's five historical layers -- @@yKeeper-era@@N measurement,
@@ySalt Ledger@@N extraction, @@dPyramid jurisdiction@@N, @@rSynod coercion@@N,
and @@gecological takeover@@N -- are a conversion nightmare. Each
overwrote the previous without erasing it. Our Shoreward Assessors
call this @@rpalimpsest jurisdiction@@N: a territory where no legal
framework holds exclusive authority and every claim references a
contradictory claim beneath.

We face a milder version at the Shoreward Seal. Inland charter
stamps reference toll authorities that may no longer exist. Desert
water-debt arrives at our tables denominated in cistern shares from
dried wells. The Assessors must translate these into maritime terms.
@@dThe canyon shows what happens when translation fails entirely.@@N

The @@d"unpaid names"@@N -- the dead whose rites were withheld pending
debt -- strike at guardian-name doctrine. In Mafdet, your guardian-
name follows you through life and death. To withhold a name because
of unpaid water-debt is to @@rbreak the most fundamental oath@@N a
community makes: that you will be remembered.

The @@rCharter Reclaimers@@N running extortion checkpoints perform
@@rpredatory attestation@@N. The Sand-Sea Carters' Guild advises:
pay the toll, keep your own records, report the coordinates. The
Ledger Houses will not recognize Reclaimer stamps, but @@ywill@@N note
the extortion as a corridor surcharge.

The @@dDustbound Court-Dead@@N -- former assessors raised by layered
rite residue -- @@rdemand declarations and escort intruders to
judgment points@@N. They perform attestation after death: process
persisting beyond the authority that created it. The Shrine of the
First Claw recognizes no oath administered by the dead.

Our Shoreward Conversion slab is basalt, not sandstone. It does not
layer or overwrite. Each oath stands alone, attested by the living,
honored because @@ysomeone with a guardian-name stands behind it@@N.
The Arroyo shows the alternative: a threshold where no one stands
behind anything. @@dWe will not be that canyon.@@N
